'''SETILive''' was an online project of [[Zooniverse (citizen science project)|Zooniverse]] that utilized live participants to analyze radio telescope data in real time to recognize patterns to find [[extraterrestrial intelligence]]s (ETI's). The project ceased live operations on 12 October 2014, but still allows archival analysis.<ref>{{cite web|title=NOTICE: Live Data Ending Oct 12|url=http://talk.setilive.org/discussions/DSL100egc1|accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref> ==Project== The project was launched in February 2012 as part of [[Jill Tarter]]'s 2009 [[TED (conference)|TED]] Prize Wish.<ref name="huffingtonpost1">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/seti-institute/seti-live_b_1310878.html |title=SETI Institute Teams Up With Zooniverse to Empower Citizen Scientists in the Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence |publisher=The Huffington Post |date=29 February 2012 |accessdate=2012-07-07}}</ref> SETILive uses data provided by the [[Allen Telescope Array]] and presents it visually so that the public can collectively search for radio signals.<ref>{{cite web|title=About SETILive|url=http://setilive.org/about|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref> The project focuses on radio frequencies that automated detection systems ignore due to the prevalence of man-made noise. Jill Tarter hopes that human analysts will be able to detect low [[signal-to-noise]] transmissions which confuse computers.<ref name="huffingtonpost1"/> The telescope scans the zone between a known star and a known planet where liquid water is possible. This is called the [[habitable zone]]. The website displays one to three different scans of an area of space. Its energy is measured and put into a [[waterfall chart|waterfall display]]. Users must identify the areas of high energy—signals—by making two points through which a line is drawn.<ref>{{cite web|title=Signals|url=http://setilive.org/gallery|publisher=SETILive|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref> Users classify signals as: broken, continuous, or parallel. Users then must classify the signal as: erratic, wide, or narrow. Many of the signals are just satellites that give off energy.
== Decoys == The makers of SETILive intentionally put some false positives in. Sometimes, When a user clicks "done", a red line will identify the simulated ETI signal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Simulations! (late, but how would Scotty have handled it?)|url=http://blog.setilive.org/2012/05/26/simulations-late-but-how-would-scotty-have-handled-it/|publisher=SETILive|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref>
