'''Z. S. Strother''' is Riggio Professor of [[African Art]] at Columbia University. Her work focuses on 20th and 21st-century Central and West African art history.
She graduated from [[Yale University]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Zoë Strother - Faculty - Department of Art History and Archaeology - Columbia University|url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/arthistory/faculty/Strother.html|website=www.columbia.edu|publisher=Columbia University|accessdate=2 March 2017}}</ref>
Strother was a 2000 [[Guggenheim Fellow]].<ref>{{cite web|title=John Simon Guggenheim Foundation {{!}} Z. S. Strother|url=http://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/z-s-strother/|website=www.gf.org|publisher=John Simon Guggenheim Foundation|accessdate=2 March 2017}}</ref> Her book ''Inventing Masks'' won the 2001 Arnold Rubin Outstanding Publication Award from the Arts Council of the [[African Studies Association]].<ref>{{cite web|title=ACASA : Arts Council of the African Studies Association|url=https://archive.is/AwcYM|website=archive.is|publisher=African Studies Association|accessdate=2 March 2017|date=5 July 2008}}</ref>
==Works== * ''Inventing Masks: Agency and History in the Art of the Central Pende'' ([[University of Chicago Press]], 1998) {{ISBN|9780226777337}}, {{OCLC|41258436}} * ''Pende'' (5 Continents Editions, 2008) {{OCLC|148864715}} * ''Vladimir Markov and Russian [[Primitivism]]: A Charter for the Avant-Garde' with Jeremy Howard and Irēna Bužinska (Ashgate, 2015) {{ISBN|9781317001027}}, {{OCLC|973229740}} * ''Humor and Violence: Seeing Europeans in Central African Art, 1850-1997'' ([[Indiana University Press]], 2016) {{ISBN|0253022673}}, {{OCLC|966825524}}
